      <h1 id="title">Yoshie Shiratori</h1>
        <p> The man that no prison can hold
        </p>
    </header>
    <main id="main">
      <title>Yoshie Shiratori</title>
        <div id="img-div">
          <img id="image" src="https://www.breakingasia.com/wp-content/uploads/Abashiri-Prison-Museum-%C2%A9Yusuke-Umezawa.jpg" alt="Abashiri prison museum photo">
          <div id="img-caption">
            <p id="image-caption">Replica of Shiratori's escape from Abashiri Prison at the Abashiri Prison Museum.</p>
          </div>
       </div>
      <div id="tribute-info">
        <p> Here's a timeline of Shiratori's life: </p>
        <ul class="tribute-timeline">
          <li>
            <b>1907</b> - born on 31 July, in Aomori, Japan 
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>1936</b> - imprisoned at Aomori Prison caused by false accusition of robbery and murder
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>1936</b> - escaped prison by picking his cell lock with a bucket metal wire and escaped through a cracked skylight
          <li>
            <b>1936</b> - recaptured by police after three days while he was stealing supplies from a hospital. Sentenced to life in prison for escaping and theft.
          </li>
          <li>
          <b>1942</b> - managed to escape from Akita Prison by climbing walls of his cell to reach the air vent. 
          </li>
          <li>
          <b>1942</b> - three months later, showed up at Guard Kobayashi’s (the only people who had shown kindness to him in the Akita prison) house to ask for help in a case against injustice in the Japanese prison system. However, the guard called the police, and he was arrested and sent back to prison.
          </li> 
          <li>
          <b>1943</b> - transferred to Abashiri prison in Northern Hokkaido, the country’s northernmost prison.
          </li>
          <li>
          <b>1944</b> - escaped the prison by dislocating both of his shoulders, enabling him to fit out of the narrow food slot in his cell door, using a wartime blackout as cover.
          </li>
          <li>
          <b>1946</b> - captured after fatally stabbing a farmer who attacked him after he was caught stealing a tomato from his farm. By now, he had made headlines on several newspapers.
          </li>
          <li>
          <b>1947</b> - sentenced to death by the Sapporo District Court. At the Sapporo prison, he dug his way out by making a tunnel with miso soup bowls.
          </li>
          <li>
          <b>1948</b> - was offered a cigarette (cigarettes were expensive after the war) by a police officer in a park. Moved by the kindness, He admitted he was an escaped convict and offered to be turned in. The High Court of Sapporo revoked his death sentence to 20 years.
          </li>
          <li>
          <b>1961</b> - released from Fuchu Prison for good behavior.
          </li>
          <li>
          <b>1979</b> - lived for another decade working odd jobs to survive. He eventually succumbed to a heart attack at the age of 71.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p id="tribute-reference"> Find out more about his great story at his <a id="tribute-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoshie_Shiratori" target="_blank">Wikipedia entry</a> and <a id="" href=https://www.breakingasia.com/japan/yoshie-shiratori-the-incredible-story-of-a-man-no-prison-could-hold/>Breaking Asia news entry</a></p>
      </div>
      </div>
